In Week 6 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been emerging snapped into clearer focus. The presidency was no longer only testing the edges of the system; it was beginning to rewire it. Power moved along three main lines: centralizing control over money and people inside the executive, repurposing the security state to protect allies and punish enemies, and tightening the flow of information so that fewer independent voices could reach the public. The week\'92s events did not yet amount to an open break with constitutional rule, but they showed how far the country had drifted toward a system where law, bureaucracy, and memory serve the ruler first and the public only incidentally. It felt less like a series of isolated fights and more like a single project carried out on many fronts at once. That project was now easier to see.\
