At the close of the previous period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:31 p.m. It now reads 7:32 p.m., a movement of just over half a minute. On its face, that is a small shift. But the clock\'92s change reflects not the volume of news but the depth of structural damage. This week, the largest movements came in traits that measure how the civil service is politicized, how executive power escapes oversight, how law is turned into a weapon, and how independent media are starved while state-aligned outlets thrive. Courts and civil servants did win some injunctions and carve-outs, and those pockets of resistance helped keep the clock from jumping further. Yet the net effect was clear. The architecture that once constrained presidents and protected neutral governance was being bent toward a narrower circle of loyalty and wealth.\
