The first major development was the consolidation of fiscal and personnel power in the hands of the president and his chosen private partner. Through a series of orders, memos, and informal commands, Trump and Elon Musk\'92s \'93Department of Government Efficiency\'94 (DOGE) moved to control who gets paid, who gets fired, and which programs live or die. The executive order implementing the DOGE cost-efficiency initiative placed this lightly defined unit at the center of all federal payments\'97contracts, grants, and loans\'97displacing the normal balance between agencies, Congress, and the Office of Management and Budget. Another order froze all government credit cards for thirty days, ostensibly to root out waste, but in practice halting routine purchases at places like the National Institutes of Health and forcing researchers to stop buying basic supplies. Work stalled. Exceptions existed on paper, but the process to obtain them was so cumbersome that most work simply stopped. In parallel, OMB and OPM sent a joint memo directing every agency to prepare mass layoff and reorganization plans by mid-March, and a separate OPM memo told agencies to reclassify top career posts as political. These moves did not just cut budgets; they shifted the levers of staffing and spending from a dispersed, rule-bound system to a single, executive-centered apparatus monitored by Musk\'92s team. Executive power became less a matter of policy direction and more a matter of direct control over the state\'92s purse and payroll.\
\
The second strand of this consolidation ran through the civil service itself. Across the government, probationary employees and specialized staff found themselves on the chopping block. The Pentagon announced layoffs of 5,400 civilian workers and a broader hiring freeze. USAID placed nearly all of its 4,700 staff on paid leave and then began eliminating roughly 2,000 positions, while the administration invited remaining workers back only long enough to collect their belongings. NOAA, the country\'92s main climate and weather agency, fired hundreds of employees\'97many of them hired under programs meant to diversify the workforce\'97and signaled that total cuts could reach 800 to 1,000 positions. The Social Security Administration announced a restructuring that might cut up to half of its 57,000 employees. The Environmental Protection Agency faced plans for a 65% budget reduction, which former administrators warned would gut its ability to protect air and water. Even the Department of Education dangled a rushed buyout of up to $25,000, less than what many would receive in a formal reduction in force, pressuring staff to leave under worse terms. Taken together, these actions did not simply shrink government; they hollowed out the neutral, expert core that had made federal agencies something more than extensions of any one administration. The civil service was being remade into a more precarious, more politicized workforce.\
\
Elon Musk\'92s role in this process blurred the line between public authority and private power. Through OPM and DOGE, he ordered all federal workers to email five accomplishments from the prior week, with failure to respond treated as a resignation. The ultimatum was backed by Trump and framed as a test of productivity, but in practice it functioned as a loyalty and fear mechanism. Some Cabinet departments, including the FBI, Justice, and Defense, told their employees to ignore the email or to hold off until legal questions were resolved. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. went the other way, instructing his staff to comply. Unions amended their lawsuits to challenge the directive under administrative law, and a federal judge later issued a temporary restraining order blocking OPM from sharing personal data with DOGE staff. Still, the message to civil servants was unmistakable. Their continued employment now depended not only on performance but on their willingness to submit to ad hoc demands from an unelected billionaire. When twenty-one DOGE employees and other civil servants resigned in protest, citing fears of compromising core systems and sensitive data, they underscored how far the internal culture had shifted from service to the public toward service to a small circle of political and corporate actors.\
