A second major development was the repurposing of the security state\'97law enforcement, intelligence, and the military\'97to protect allies and intimidate opponents. At the Justice Department, Attorney General Pam Bondi created a \'93weaponization working group\'94 that reported not to career leadership but to Stephen Miller in the White House. Its mandate was to review supposed abuses of the criminal justice system over the prior four years, a frame that cast prosecutions of Trump and his allies as political vendettas to be undone. In Washington, interim U.S. Attorney Ed Martin declared on social media that his office and other federal prosecutors were \'93President Trump\'92s lawyers,\'94 a direct repudiation of their oath to the Constitution. He had already promised to protect Elon Musk\'92s interests and to revisit Capitol riot cases after Trump\'92s pardons. In the same week, Trump suspended the security clearances of lawyers from the firm that had represented former special counsel Jack Smith, using classification authority to handicap legal adversaries. Law, in these moves, became less a neutral limit on power and more a tool to be aimed at enemies and lifted from friends.\
