The FBI and the military saw parallel shifts. Trump installed Kash Patel, a loyalist with far-right sympathies, as FBI director, and Dan Bongino, a conspiracy-minded media figure, as his deputy. One of Patel\'92s first acts was to relocate up to 1,500 agents out of the J. Edgar Hoover Building, including counterterrorism and national security investigators, and to signal that far-right extremist groups would no longer be a priority. Instead, he spoke of focusing on Black Lives Matter, antifascist activists, and the media. At the Pentagon, Trump and Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth fired General Charles Q. Brown Jr., the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, along with Admiral Lisa Franchetti and other senior leaders, and moved to nominate a less qualified loyalist as the new chair. Hegseth also announced plans to dismiss the judge advocates general of the Army, Navy, and Air Force\'97the lawyers responsible for military justice\'97on the theory that they might obstruct \'93tough\'94 orders. At the same time, the Pentagon ordered the services to identify and discharge transgender troops and to scrub references to diversity, equity, and inclusion from their websites. These steps did not yet amount to a formal coup, but they reoriented the coercive arms of the state toward loyalty tests, culture-war targets, and impunity for the president\'92s movement. The security state\'92s center of gravity shifted.\
