The treatment of January 6 defendants illustrated how this new security posture worked in practice. Trump pardoned Enrique Tarrio, the former Proud Boys leader convicted of seditious conspiracy, along with roughly 1,500 other participants in the Capitol attack. He then expanded some pardons to cover gun and drug charges. Pardoned figures held a press conference at the Capitol, reenacted parts of their actions from that day, and announced plans to sue the Justice Department for prosecuting them. Tarrio was arrested again for assaulting a protester, but the larger message was that those who commit violence on the president\'92s behalf can expect protection. Bomb threats invoking \'93Emperor Trump\'94 forced the evacuation of the Principles First summit, a gathering of anti-Trump conservatives, and targeted speakers like former officer Michael Fanone. These threats, combined with the pardons, signaled that paramilitary intimidation aligned with the regime would be tolerated, while legal tools would be turned against those who had enforced the law in the past. Accountability became selective.\
