A third development was the systematic hollowing of expert governance in science, health, climate, and social insurance. At NIH, the administration blocked the publication of study-section notices in the Federal Register, effectively freezing the peer-review process for some 16,000 grant applications worth $1.5 billion. Internal memos showed that DEI-related grants were being flagged and held despite a federal court\'92s temporary restraining order prohibiting such a freeze. Trump also issued an order limiting NIH\'92s ability to pay indirect costs, which support lab infrastructure and staff, though a judge had blocked that as well. The practical result was an indefinite lapse in funding for research on cancer, heart disease, and other conditions, even as a measles outbreak claimed the life of an unvaccinated child in Texas. At the same time, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention canceled a meeting of its Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices, and the Food and Drug Administration canceled its meeting to select flu strains for the coming season\'92s vaccines, despite a severe flu year. Health Secretary Kennedy\'92s department announced plans to eliminate public participation in many HHS policy decisions, reversing his earlier promise of \'93radical transparency.\'94 Public health and biomedical science, once buffered by process and expert committees, were now subject to abrupt political interruption. The guardrails were thinner.\
