Climate and environmental science faced similar blows. Beyond the NOAA layoffs and budget cuts, the administration demanded access to NOAA\'92s IT systems and editorial control over intranet sites, and it ordered the removal of DEI and climate references from agency communications. The Environmental Protection Agency continued to issue routine rules and information-collection notices on air pollution, hazardous emissions, and water quality, but these technocratic acts now sat atop a shrinking staff and a threatened budget. The Department of Agriculture, having earlier fired workers fighting a bird flu outbreak, scrambled to rehire some of them as the crisis worsened. The pattern was not one of simple neglect; it was a deliberate weakening of the state\'92s capacity to gather data, enforce standards, and respond to emergencies, followed by ad hoc reversals when the consequences became too stark to ignore. Expertise became something to be cut first and restored only under duress.\
