The fourth major development lay in information and media control. The White House escalated its campaign against independent press and narrative autonomy. After Trump signed an order renaming the Gulf of Mexico as the \'93Gulf of America,\'94 the administration barred the Associated Press from the Oval Office, Air Force One, and other events because it refused to adopt the new term. A federal judge declined to issue a temporary restraining order restoring AP\'92s access, distinguishing these spaces as \'93more private,\'94 and the administration took that as license to go further. White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt announced that the White House, not the White House Correspondents\'92 Association, would now decide which reporters could join the presidential press pool. Reuters lost its traditional spot, and at a joint press conference with France\'92s Emmanuel Macron, Trump called first on a far-right journalist. In a separate Oval Office meeting with Ukraine\'92s Volodymyr Zelensky, Western outlets like AP and Reuters were excluded while a Russian state news agency reporter was initially admitted. These choices did not just punish critical coverage; they restructured the information environment so that state-aligned and foreign authoritarian voices had privileged access to the American presidency. Independent media were pushed to the margins.\
