The administration also leaned into new tools of propaganda and spectacle. On social media, Trump shared an AI-generated video of a fictional \'93Trump Gaza\'94 resort, complete with a golden statue of himself and images of Gaza redeveloped as a luxury destination after the removal of Palestinians. Another official video depicted migrants in shackles on a deportation flight, marketed as \'93ASMR: Illegal Alien Deportation Flight.\'94 Both pieces used digital imagery to turn human suffering and geopolitical upheaval into entertainment and branding. At the Department of Housing and Urban Development, hackers briefly took over building screens to show a satirical AI video of Trump kissing Elon Musk\'92s feet, underscoring both the vulnerability of government systems and the centrality of digital images in the political struggle. Meanwhile, Attorney General Bondi released a limited set of Jeffrey Epstein files not to Congress but to right-wing influencers like Jack Posobiec and Chaya Raichik, while refusing to provide fuller records to a House investigative committee. The files, including Epstein\'92s phonebook, were thin on new substance but rich in potential for selective amplification. In this way, the state\'92s control over archives and access became another lever for shaping public memory. What could not be controlled could be sidelined.\
