A fifth development concerned the stratification of citizenship and belonging. Trump used the stage at CPAC to announce what he called the largest deportation operation in American history, framed as a response to an \'93invasion\'94 at the southern border. His administration ordered ICE to deport hundreds of thousands of unaccompanied migrant children, directed the Pentagon and Homeland Security to prepare a 30,000-bed detention facility at Guantanamo Bay for \'93the worst criminal illegal aliens,\'94 and then began housing migrants there under conditions of shackling, cages, strip searches, and isolation. The State Department imposed permanent visa bans on transgender athletes and required that undocumented immigrants aged fourteen and older register with USCIS and provide fingerprints, with penalties for noncompliance. At the same time, Trump proposed a $5 million \'93Gold Card\'94 that would give wealthy buyers a path to citizenship, and he floated a Trump-branded Gold Card as a route to permanent residency. Citizenship and legal presence were thus being sorted along lines of wealth, gender identity, and origin: harsh detention and expulsion for the poor and marginalized, and a purchasable path for the rich. Belonging became a graded status.\
