These domestic moves were mirrored in foreign policy. At the United Nations, the United States voted against a General Assembly resolution condemning Russian aggression in Ukraine, aligning itself with Russia, Belarus, and a handful of other states, even as ninety-three countries voted in favor. The U.S. delegation also backed Security Council language that took a more conciliatory line toward Moscow, and Trump directed his officials to negotiate peace terms directly with Russia, excluding Ukraine and European allies. In public, he refused to call Vladimir Putin a dictator while labeling Zelensky one. In a contentious Oval Office meeting, Trump and Senator J.D. Vance berated Zelensky, demanded mineral rights in exchange for military aid, and suggested halting all shipments. A minerals-for-aid deal was later announced, offering Ukraine $350 billion in military support in exchange for access to critical resources but no long-term security guarantees. At the same time, the administration cut funding for UNAIDS and suspended foreign aid that had been providing healthcare to Myanmar refugees, leading to deaths when clinics closed. It pressured Romania to lift travel bans on Andrew Tate, an influencer facing trafficking and abuse charges, and celebrated when he arrived in Florida. In Gaza, Trump and Jared Kushner advanced plans to remove Palestinians and redevelop the strip as a luxury resort, with Kushner convening real estate developers and raising billions from foreign sovereign funds. Foreign policy, in these episodes, became a blend of authoritarian alignment, transactional bargaining, and private enrichment.\
